{{Infobox artist | name = Naomi Uman | image = | caption = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[New York City]], [[United States]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality =American | education = [[California Institute of the Arts]], 1998 | movement =[[Feminism]] | patrons = | bgcolour = #6495ED | imagesize = | field = [[Video art]], [[Film director]], [[Visual artist]] | works = Leche, Removed, Unnamed Film, Videodiary 2-1-2006 To The Present | influenced by = | influenced = }}
'''Naomi Uman''' is an American experimental filmmaker and a visual artist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lift.ca/programming/naomi-uman-winter-2016-artist-residence|title=Naomi Uman - Winter 2016 Artist in Residence {{!}} Liaison of Independent Filmmakers of Toronto|website=lift.ca|access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref> Uman received an&nbsp;MFA&nbsp;in [[Filmmaking]] from [[CalArts]] in 1998.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://creative-capital.org/grantees/view/111/project:92|title=Creative Capital - Investing in Artists who Shape the Future|website=creative-capital.org|access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref> Uman's work is often "marked by her signature handmade aesthetic, often shooting, hand-processing and editing her films with the most rudimentary of practices."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://peripheralproduce.com/artists/naomi-uman|title=Naomi Uman|website=Peripheral Produce|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref> Once private chef to [[Gloria Vanderbilt]], [[Malcolm Forbes]], and [[Calvin Klein (fashion designer)|Calvin Klein]]. Her award-winning films have screened widely at major international festivals as well as the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum|Guggenheim Museum]], the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], and the [[Museo de Arte Moderno]] in Mexico City.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://expcinema.org/site/en/tags/naomi-uman|title=Naomi Uman|website=Experimental Cinema|access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref>
==Filmography==
<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hallwalls.org/media-arts/4413.html|title=Naomi Uman - 5 FILMS BY NAOMI UMAN - 11/19/05|website=www.hallwalls.org|access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecinematheque.ca/dim/ukrainian-time-machine-living-films-naomi-uman|title=Ukrainian Time Machine: Living Films by Naomi Uman {{!}} The Cinematheque|website=www.thecinematheque.ca|access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref> * Leche (1998, 16mm, b&w, sound, 30 min.) * Tin Woodsman (2008, 16mm, color, sound, 6 min.) * Removed (1999, 16mm, color, sound, 6 min.) * Lay (2006, 16mm, b&w, sound, 15 min.) * Coda (2008, 16mm, b&w, sound, 3 min.) * Kalendar (2008, 16mm, color, silent, 11 min.) * On this Day (2006, 16mm, color, sound, 4 min.) * Unnamed Film (2008, 16mm, color/b&w, sound, 55 min.)
==Awards== Uman was awarded the [[Guggenheim Fellowship]] for Film, US & Canada in [[List of Guggenheim Fellowships awarded in 2002|2002]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/naomi-uman/|title=John Simon Guggenheim Foundation {{!}} Naomi Uman|website=www.gf.org|access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref> In 2008 she was awarded a Media Arts Fellowship by [[Tribeca Film Institute]].<ref name=":0" />
